{
  "texts": [
    "Conversely, a Lie algebra bundle isomorphism f ad: adM 1 → adM 2 satisfying (i) and (ii) gives rise to a fibre-preserving isometry f: (M 1, g 1) → (M 2, g 2).Proof.",
    "Since f is a fibre-preserving isometry, we havef * (V 1) = V 2 and f * (H 1) = H 2.",
    "Also, f covers a diffeomorphism f: B 1 → B 2, which is isometric since for p ∈ π -1 1 (b) ⊂ M 1, its differential is a composition of local isometries: d fb = dπ 2 • df p • dπ 1 | -1 H1.",
    "Given b ∈ B 1, the restricted map f | M b: M 1,b → M 2, f (b)is an isometry between fibres.",
    "Since the fibres admit simply-transitive isometric actions by a nilpotent Lie group, [Wil82] implies thatf | M b: (M 1,b, ∇ V1,b) → (M 2, f (b), ∇ V2, f (b))is an affine diffeomorphism with respect to the canonical vertical connections (Section 2.1)."
  ]
}